title: For Sale:  Enfield No 4 Mk 2  .303 British
postcontent: This is a post "Irish Contract" No. 4 Mk 2 that was made in 1955. The thing that made the Irish rifles special was the fact that they were never issued and sat in a warehouse until they were released. This rifle had the same thing happen, but it sat in a British warehouse instead. These were the last and the best Enfields that were manufactured, but Britian had so many others in use that they didn't need these before they adopted the FAL for standard issue. This particular rifle was thouroughly cleaned and the stock was coated with Linseed oil like it was supposed to be. I was supposed to hit it with 0000 steel wool to take the shine off, but it looked kinda cool so I left it. I'll finish it for the purchaser if they wish. Of course all of the numbers match including the stock, but there is no number on the magazine. It also has the flip-up long range rear sight. I have 148 Mk7 surplus rounds (1964), 49 S&B match rounds, and 20 Federal SP hunting rounds that I'll throw in. That's over 217 rounds if you weren't counting. If you need more pictures (I would!) or information, please don't hesitate to ask. I would be interested in trades other than firearms, I'm thinning the herd as it is.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Polytech AKS-762 AK47 Preban Spiker, extremely nice collector piece
postcontent: Hello, you are viewing a beautiful Poly Technologies INC PREBAN AKS-762 AK47 7.62x39MM. If the add is up the rifle is available. Imported by KFS Atlanta, GA. This is a factory 386 CW- model. The "C" Series Polys were the rifles with the improvements  factory, spring loaded firing pin, checkered pistol grips, under folding bayonet. These rifles were only imported for two years 1988 to 1989 before the import ban. I purchased this package quite some time ago solely as an investment firearm. I'm not a big ak fan so this is only one of two I've owned, but this is one of the rolls royce of Chinese AK,S. Any polytech model now is highly collectible, especially since none have been legally imported since the end of the 80,s. Rifle comes with a certificate of authenticity from polytech illustrating the story behind this rifle from production factory and date, along with original sale date, factory it was made in. If your not familiar with polytech check out the info as it's quite the amazing story.  Rifle comes with 5 Chinese magazines, green sling, green oil container, certificate, original operator manual, and two different product brochures,original polytech tool kit still in plastic, and an original polytech box. The box doesn't appear to be the factory box as I purchased the package and the original owner had it in a wheeled hard case so a mixup must have happened when we were going through his collection of polytech rifles. Please ask any questions, I will do my best to try and answer any questions. I cannot tell you how many rounds have been down the pipe as I've never fired the rifle. I can tell you it's minimal as this rifle is in amazing shape But doesn't come with a round counter installed :) After so many years. Rifling, wood and all metal are awesome. Bright shiny bore, all metal without any rust or corrosion, blonde wood looks amazing, spikes bayonet folds and extends perfectly. Kept cleaned, oiled, in climate controlled safes since the day I had it. Would make one heck of a shooter or collector for you AK fans.

title: For Sale:  Colt AR-15 Sporter Heavy-Barrel Match Rifle 5.56 NATO
postcontent: Selling my 1992 factory original Colt AR-15 Sporter Heavy-Barrel Match Rifle, 5.56 Nato, 1:7 twist, chrome lined, magnetic partical tested barrel, and adjustable front & rear match sites, has been test fired and stored, so it's still in mint condition. (serial number MH043xx) Buyer beware, because Colt started making new Sporter's a few years ago, and they look very similar to the originals, but they are not the same quality. The new ones can be had for about $900, and I have noticed that some of the new ones are being sold/represented as one of the older original Sporter's, or Pre Ban Sporter. A preban Sporter is one that was made prior to the assault rifle ban law of 1984, which expired in 1994. Because it may be hard for a novice to tell the difference, I recommend getting the serial number and calling Colt to verify the date of manufacture. The book value for my rifle, which was made in 1992, which makes it an original Colt Sporter Heavy-Barrel Match rifle, is $2,150 to $2,350. An original Pre-Ban Sporter in mint conditon would be worth even more.

title: For Sale:  USED RUGER M77 24"BARREL 30-06 W/SCOPE
postcontent:
Used Ruger M77 24" Barrel
Cal: 30-06
Scope: Redfield 3x-9x
From the beginning, the Ruger M77 was intended as a modernized Mauser 98, though numerous changes were made. Bill Ruger wanted to use investment casting in place of a forged receiver. The Sullivan-designed bolt dispensed with the Mauser blade type ejector and instead used the simpler plunger style of ejector. A two-position tang safety and redesigned trigger system were also designed from scratch.
Perhaps the most novel feature of the M77 is the only one that has not been redesigned, the angled action screw. The front action screw of traditional bolt-action rifles draws the receiver directly down against the stock. The M77 uses an angled screw that draws the action down and to the rear, tightly bedding it against the stock.
